<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1231,1436]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[151,272,1232,1255]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small species, shorter than 
<quantity box="[583,667,1231,1255]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
(often shorter than 2.0 mm), usually with short, oval elytra, and with integument, at least in part, reddish (except for 
<taxonomicName box="[678,874,1268,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Mecinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albocutellatus">
<emphasis box="[678,874,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">M. albocutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); protibiae with apical part of ventral surface only weakly directed outward; penis having flagellum with one to four rings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1231,1436]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[199,567,1340,1364]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Remarks and comparative notes.</emphasis>
This assemblage of species is formed by several taxa, which are mostly very similar to each other but lacking synapomorphies. Therefore they seem to represent the most primitive species in the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
